comments.body: closed by #2489

The error message in Honeybadger says "NoMethodError: undefined method `with_indifferent_access' for nil:NilClass" for this URL: https://catalog.princeton.edu/requests/1873599?mfhd=1873599&source=firestone_locator1873599

This seems caused due to lack of validation in the Requests app, from the Honeybadger stacktrace it seems that the issue is in [build_requestable_from_data](https://github.com/pulibrary/requests/blob/main/app/models/requests/request.rb#L250-L255)

```
def build_requestable_from_data
        return if doc[:holdings_1display].nil?
        @mfhd ||= 'thesis' if thesis?
        @mfhd ||= 'numismatics' if numismatics?
        [build_requestable_from_holding(@mfhd, holdings[@mfhd].with_indifferent_access)]
end
```

My guess is that the `mfdh` is not valid and that's why `holdings[@mfhd].with_indifferent_access` throws an error.

This record is in ETAS, https://catalog.princeton.edu/catalog/1873599 so no one should be requesting it or being referred by any of our applications to request it at the moment. I see the book locator is created the URL that generated the error, this is old functionality that we should remove from it when we circle back to updating it for alma (it used to it's own version of availability that this link is a vestige of:
https://catalog.princeton.edu/requests/1873599?mfhd=1873599&source=firestone_locator1873599.

comments.body:
I'm seeing similar behavior with CDH staging sites that are IP restricted, and suspect it may also be happening with errors being served to google and bing search bots (google search console is reporting a suspiciously large number of "soft 404s" for the CDH website, meaning content is not found but it was not served with a 404 or other status).

You can easily duplicate the problem by using curl on an IP restricted site while not on VPN, e.g.:
> curl -I https://test-geniza.cdh.princeton.edu
```
HTTP/2 200
server: nginx/1.19.10
date: Mon, 07 Jun 2021 16:43:00 GMT
content-type: text/html
content-length: 2489
last-modified: Fri, 04 Jun 2021 20:39:29 GMT
etag: "60ba8f81-9b9"
accept-ranges: bytes
```

I see that both prod and staging maintenance.conf `@maintenance` locations include a `=502` directive.

Based on [this stackoverflow answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/57562136) I think maybe it is returning 200 because the `try_files` succeeds on finding `index.html`, although that's not clear to me from the nginx documentation for `try_files`

comments.body: @dependabot rebase
Superseded by #841.

This issue is still happening (see https://app.honeybadger.io/projects/65922/faults/78580571)

I believe the culprit is in the [get collections routes](https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/blob/main/config/routes.rb#L38-L47). On a minimal Rails application the problem seems to be that we are preserving the `|` in the redirect. The following change should take care of the problem:

```
get "/collections/:eadid/:componentid", constraints: { eadid: /([^\/])+?/ }, to: redirect { |params, _request|
  "/catalog/#{params[:eadid].tr('.', '-').tr('|', '-')}_#{params[:componentid].tr('|', '-')}"
}
      
get "/collections/:eadid", constraints: { eadid: /([^\/])+?/ }, format: /json|xml|html/, to: redirect { |params, _request|
  "/catalog/#{params[:eadid].tr('.', '-').tr('|', '-')}"
}
```

Notice the `.tr('|', '-')` to replace the `|` with a `-` in both `eadid` and `compoentid` before the redirect.
@dependabot rebase
